          "body": "The bulk of the chapter (vv.12-38) is devoted to the Feast of Tabernacles (*Sukkot*), Israel's most jubilant festival, celebrating the harvest and commemorating the wilderness sojourn. Its sacrificial calendar is the most elaborate in the Pentateuch: across seven days plus an eighth-day closing assembly, Israel would offer 71 bulls, 15 rams, 105 lambs, and 8 male goats — plus all their accompanying grain and drink offerings. The bulls, uniquely, descend daily: 13, 12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7. The rabbinic tradition, noted in the Talmud (*Sukkah* 55b), reads the total of 70 bulls as intercession for the 70 nations of Genesis 10 — the table of nations representing all humanity. This universalist reading is consistent with Zechariah 14:16-17, which prophesies that the nations will one day come to Jerusalem to celebrate the Feast of Tabernacles. Whether or not the exact numerology was part of Moses' intent, the canonical witness is clear: Israel's most lavish worship had a scope wider than Israel."
